        {
            "id": "061e722d14f944e4b5884",
            "questionText": "An artificial satellite with a mass ($!$m = 1500$!$ kg) is orbiting the Earth in an elliptical orbit. At its perigee (closest approach), the satellite is at a distance ($!$r_p = 7 \\times 10^6$!$ m) from the Earth's center and has a speed ($!$v_p = 8000$!$ m/s). At its apogee (farthest point), the satellite is at a distance ($!$r_a = 21 \\times 10^6$!$ m) from the Earth's center. Calculate the total energy ($!$E_T$!$) of the satellite in its orbit.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "1de37bd8057a4df2b1e09",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recalling the formula to determine the semi-major axis $!$a$!$ of an elliptical orbit in terms of the perigee $!$r_p$!$ and apogee $!$r_a$!$. Please identify the correct formula among the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "a = $!$(r_p + r_a)/2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "a = $!$2r_a - r_p$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "a = $!$\\sqrt{r_p \\times r_a}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "495cf3b8217e4bbc89913",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the formula you identified, calculate the semi-major axis $!$a$!$ given that $!$r_p = 7 \\times 10^6 \\; m$!$ and $!$r_a = 21 \\times 10^6 \\; m$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.4e7"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "68d19191a9ea4acd942c6",
                    "stepText": "Next, recall the formula for the total orbital energy of a satellite in an elliptical orbit in terms of $!$GM$!$, $!$m$!$, and $!$a$!$. Please select the correct formula from the options provided.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea1e89e6-51eb-4c26-9db9-4af747efca26"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "E = $!$-\\frac{GMm}{2a}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "E = $!$-\\frac{GMm}{a}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "E = $!$-\\frac{GMm}{a^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "7283542e639f459da677c",
                    "stepText": "Now, compute the numerator part $!$GMm$!$ using the provided values: Earth's gravitational parameter $!$GM = 3.986 \\times 10^{14} \\; m^3/s^2$!$ and the satellite's mass $!$m = 1500 \\; kg$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "5.979e17"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg*m^3/s^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea1e89e6-51eb-4c26-9db9-4af747efca26"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "7f909f9b519e4be9b0bb7",
                    "stepText": "Now calculate the denominator of the energy formula, which is $!$2a$!$. Use the semi-major axis you computed earlier.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.8e7"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea1e89e6-51eb-4c26-9db9-4af747efca26"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "3c7c075499734501ad7b7",
                    "stepText": "Finally, substitute the numerator and the denominator into the total energy formula to calculate $!$E_T$!$. Remember that the formula includes a negative sign. Compute the value accordingly.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "-2.14e10"
                    ],
